Aegla Leach, 1820
is the only genus of Anomura exclusively adapted to freshwater (
), with 93 species described (Marçal et al . 2021), endemic to temperate and subtropical regions of southern South America (
). The species occur in river basins in Argentina , Bolivia , Brazil , Chile , Paraguay , and Uruguay , where they represent one of the most abundant and richest genera among freshwater crustaceans in these territories (
). Aeglids can be considered important bioindicators of water quality (
;
;
) and are of great importance in aquatic food chains (
; Verossi et al . 2014;
).

As aeglids are restricted to low-order rivers (

; 

; 

; 

) and the 
Paraná
River is a very large river, these watersheds probably constitute areas of isolation in relation to gene flow between populations and may facilitate vicariant events.

BP3 drains an area of about 
8,000 km
2
with intensive agricultural activity (

). Currently this basin suffers diversified anthropic influences and the main impacts are the intense deforestation for agricultural activities (approximately 60% of the native vegetation was removed; 

), the indiscriminate and intensive use of pesticides, the overexploitation of water and the low level of domestic sewage treatment (

). All these impacts pose an imminent risk to the preservation and maintenance of biodiversity, as well as the basin (

).

Aegla
is probably the most severely endangered group of freshwater decapod crustaceans in South America (Bueno et al. 2016), since approximately 70% of the species are under some level of threat of extinction, or in some degree of vulnerability (
). The conservation of this fauna, therefore, must be considered a very high priority (Marçal et al . 2021) and one of the premises for biological conservation is the correct identification of species (
).

Inventories of the stream fauna of BP3 are scarce. Although there are studies of the ichthyofauna (Gubiani, 
et al
. 2010; 

; 

), there are no recent works on decapods from this region and the only species of 

Aegla

recorded in these drainages is 

Aegla parana
Schmitt, 1942

(

), whose 
type
locality is found in the Iguaçu River basin.

Genomic DNA was extracted from tissues preserved in absolute alcohol, using MagMax Kits (Applied Biosystems) and Wizard® Genomic DNA Purification (Promega), following the manufacturers' recommendations. The cytochrome c oxidase subunit I mitochondrial gene region (COI, ~900 bp) was amplified using COI-f and COI-r primers (
), following the PCR conditions proposed by Pérez-Losada et al . (2002) adapted by Marçal et al. (2021). PCR products were stained with SYBR® Safe DNA Gel Stain (Life Technologies) and visualized on 1% agarose gel. Subsequently, they were purified with ExoSAP IT® (Prodimol Biotecnologia) and sequenced. Sequencing reactions were performed independently for both strands using the Big Dye Terminator Kit v 3.1 (Applied Biosystems) and the product of the sequencing reactions was analyzed on an ABI 3500 XL automated sequencer (Applied Biosystems Inc., CA, USA ). Sequences were aligned and edited in MEGA v. 6 (
). For the analysis, sequences of
Aegla species
were added, which are also available on GenBank.

